# November 30th - December 7th

## Updates

The release of Perl 5.22.1 was postponed to handle and review
a few hexfp bugs which were discovered on release of RC3. Steve
Hay's
[post](http://www.nntp.perl.org/group/perl.perl5.porters/232964)
has the voting file link.

[Term::ANSIColor](https://metacpan.org/pod/Term::ANSIColor)
4.04 is released! More information is available in the
[announcement](http://www.nntp.perl.org/group/perl.perl5.porters/233156).

[podlators](https://metacpan.org/release/podlators/)
(consisting of [Pod::Man](https://metacpan.org/pod/Pod::Man)
and [Pod::Text](https://metacpan.org/pod/Pod::Text))
4.00
[released](http://www.nntp.perl.org/group/perl.perl5.porters/232963)!

Soon thereafter, versions 4.01, 4.02, and 4.03 were released
as well.

The Mac OS 10.9 compiler has compilation problems on ithreads
builds since Jarkko Hietaniemi introduced a commit that adds
[clang](https://clang.org) thread safety analysis annotations
to the perl source code. With the help of Aaron Crane, it was
decided to only support this when using a later version of clang.

## Bugs

### Reported bugs

* [Perl #126794](https://rt.perl.org/Ticket/Display.html?id=126794):
  `$Config{installsitescript}` not populated.
* [Perl #126812](https://rt.perl.org/Ticket/Display.html?id=126812):
  Feature request for
  [Data::Dumper](https://metacpan.org/pod/Data::Dumper) to support
  condensed ranges.
* [Perl #126813](https://rt.perl.org/Ticket/Display.html?id=126813):
  Feature request for
  [Data::Dumper](https://metacpan.org/pod/Data::Dumper) to support
  tailing commas in list output.
* [Perl #126814](https://rt.perl.org/Ticket/Display.html?id=126814):
  Feature request for
  [Data::Dumper](https://metacpan.org/pod/Data::Dumper) to support
  tighter packing options.
* [Perl #126815](https://rt.perl.org/Ticket/Display.html?id=126815):
  Segfault discovered by fuzzing. Possibly a dup of
  [Perl #125540](https://rt.perl.org/Ticket/Display.html?id=125540).
* [Perl #126837](https://rt.perl.org/Ticket/Display.html?id=126837):
  Segfault in a custom `perl -d:KP` after loading
  [Time::HiRes](https://metacpan.org/pod/Time::HiRes).

### Resolved bugs

* [Perl #121048](https://rt.perl.org/Ticket/Display.html?id=121048),
  [Perl #125341](https://rt.perl.org/Ticket/Display.html?id=125341),
  and
  [Perl #125789](https://rt.perl.org/Ticket/Display.html?id=125789):
  Illegal sub declaration crashes.
* [Perl #123991](https://rt.perl.org/Ticket/Display.html?id=123991):
  Null pointer dereference.
* [Perl #126245](https://rt.perl.org/Ticket/Display.html?id=126245):
  perlapi `SvLEN_set` documentation confusingly similar to
  `SvCUR_set`.
* [Perl #126260](https://rt.perl.org/Ticket/Display.html?id=126260):
  Division by zero error.
* [Perl #126437](https://rt.perl.org/Ticket/Display.html?id=126437):
  `hex` documentation not clear on invalid input.
* [Perl #126608](https://rt.perl.org/Ticket/Display.html?id=126608):
  **lookahead** or **look-ahead**? The former!
* [Perl #126735](https://rt.perl.org/Ticket/Display.html?id=126735):
  Perl debugging disconnecting problem.
* [Perl #126753](https://rt.perl.org/Ticket/Display.html?id=126753):
  Move Win32 `$^X` code to where the `$^X` code for other OSes live.
* Proposed patch to make `-O` in `Configure` the default.

## Proposed patches

Bulk88 proposed a revised patch in
[Perl #126686](https://rt.perl.org/Ticket/Display.html?id=126686)
(build-time parallelness).

Tony Cook provided a proposed patch for handling unnecessary
rebuilds, described in
[Perl #126710](https://rt.perl.org/Ticket/Display.html?id=126710).

Sullivan Beck provided a
[patch](http://www.nntp.perl.org/group/perl.perl5.porters/233029)
to update [Locale::Codes](https://metacpan.org/pod/Locale::Codes).

Doug Bell provided a patch in
[Perl #126821](https://rt.perl.org/Ticket/Display.html?id=126821)
to mention the use of `$?` in backticks documentation. This patch
had already been merged.

Achim Gratz provided a patch in
[Perl #126834](https://rt.perl.org/Ticket/Display.html?id=126834)
to fix a Cygwin-related test.

## Discussion

Yves Orton
[suggests](http://www.nntp.perl.org/group/perl.perl5.porters/232974)
setting `SVf_POK`, `SVf_IOK`, and `SVf_NOK` flags only when on
setting and not on conversion. This will allow differentiating
between what a type **is** (in a manner of speaking) and **how**
you can use it. The suggestion and the responses are an interesting
read that detail some of the difficulties in types in dynamic
languages.

Dave Mitchell
[raised](http://www.nntp.perl.org/group/perl.perl5.porters/233053)
a discussion the semantics of `@_` with signature subroutines.

Hanno BÃ¶ck
[noted](http://www.nntp.perl.org/group/perl.perl5.porters/232983)
a possibly unnecessary wrapper script generated by `Makefile.SH`,
but as Andy Dougherty
[explains](http://www.nntp.perl.org/group/perl.perl5.porters/232991),
it is not as simple as it looks.

Dave Mitchell helped debug
[Perl #126261](https://rt.perl.org/Ticket/Display.html?id=126261)
and Karl Williamson provides more details and is working on a fix.

Ed Avis is looking at standardizing more documentation and words
with different spelling. Now looking at **regex** vs. **regexp**,
Ed [asks](http://www.nntp.perl.org/group/perl.perl5.porters/233016)
which should be used. Opinions differ, as usual.

Karl Williamson is
[noting](http://www.nntp.perl.org/group/perl.perl5.porters/233072)
that `Porting/bench.pl` does not include `utf8_heavy.pl` in its
results.

Karl also
[inquired](http://www.nntp.perl.org/group/perl.perl5.porters/233125)
about utf8 support in identifier names.
